TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Decision to Blow the Whistle: A Social Information Processing Framework
AU  - Gundlach, Michael J.
AU  - Douglas, Scott C.
AU  - Martinko, Mark J.
Y1  - 2003/01/01
PY  - 2003
DA  - 2003/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2003.8925239
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2003.8925239
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 107
EP  - 123
VL  - 28
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In this article we integrate the power, justice, and prosocial literature on whistle-blowing with the attribution and emotion literature to develop a social information processing model. This model illustrates how individuals' attributions and responsibility judgments for wrongdoing, as well as their cost-benefit analyses of acting, influence their emotions and decisions to blow the whistle. In addition, we demonstrate how wrongdoers can use impression management tactics to manipulate whistle-blowing decisions.
AB  - In this article we integrate the power, justice, and prosocial literature on whistle-blowing with the attribution and emotion literature to develop a social information processing model. This model illustrates how individuals' attributions and responsibility judgments for wrongdoing, as well as their cost-benefit analyses of acting, influence their emotions and decisions to blow the whistle. In addition, we demonstrate how wrongdoers can use impression management tactics to manipulate whistle-blowing decisions.
